cost-effective than ESS with EFS or medical management. ESS without EFS compared 
to medical management yielded an ICER of $9,004/quality-adjusted life year 
(QALY). ESS with EFS compared to ESS without EFS yielded an ICER of 
$62,310/QALY. At a willingness-to-pay (WTP) threshold of $50,000/QALY, ESS 
without EFS was more cost-effective than ESS with EFS with 52.1% certainty. 
These results were robust to one-way analysis and probabilistic sensitivity 
analysis.
CONCLUSIONS: ESS remains a cost-effective intervention compared to medical 
therapy alone for patients with CRSwNP. In this study, the addition of frontal 
sinusotomy during ESS for patients with CRSwNP was not found to be 
cost-effective at a WTP threshold of $50,000/QALY, but may be cost effective at 
a higher threshold of $100,000/QALY.
LEVEL OF EVIDENCE: 2c. Laryngoscope, 128:43-51, 2018.

