An analogy between socioeconomic deprivation level and loss of health from 
adverse effects of medical treatment in England.

Lunevicius R(1)(2), Haagsma JA(3)(4).

Author information:
(1)Emergency General Surgery and Major Trauma Centre, Aintree University 
Hospital NHS Foundation Trust, Liverpool, UK.
(2)School of Medicine, University of Liverpool, UK.
(3)Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation, University of Washington, 
Seattle, Washington, USA.
(4)Erasmus University Medical Center, Rotterdam, The Netherlands.

BACKGROUND: The purpose of this study was to show whether and how levels, trends 
and patterns obtained from estimates of premature deaths from adverse effects 
(AEs) of medical treatment depended on the deprivation level in England over the 
24-year period, 1990-2013. We provide a report to inform decision-making 
strategies to reduce the burden of disease arising from AEs of medical treatment 
in the most deprived areas of the country.
METHODS: Comparative analysis was driven by a single cause-of-injury 
category-AEs of medical treatment-from the Global Burden of Disease 2013 study. 
We report the mean values with 95% uncertainty intervals (UIs) for five 
socioeconomic deprivation areas of England.
RESULTS: In the most deprived areas of England, the death rate declined from 
2.27 (95% UI 1.65 to 2.57) to 1.54 (1.28 to 2.08) deaths (32.16% change). The 
death rate in the least deprived areas was 1.22 (0.88 to 1.38) in 1990; it was 
1.17 (0.97 to 1.59) in 2013 (4.1% change). Regarding disability-adjusted life 
year (DALY) rates, the same trend is observed. Although the gap between the most 
deprived and least deprived populations of England narrowed with regards to 
number of deaths, and rates of deaths and DALYs from AEs of medical treatment, 
inequalities between marginal levels of deprivation remain.
CONCLUSIONS: The study suggests that a relationship between deprivation level 
and health loss from the AEs of medical treatment across England is possible. 
This could then be used when devising and prioritising health policies and 
strategies.

